Below is a very detailed step-by-step guide to create storage (Amazon S3) in AWS using Terraform. I will include every small step so you can follow it easily. 🚀


---

Creating Storage in AWS (S3) Using Terraform – Step by Step

1. Create an AWS Account

1. Go to Amazon Web Services website
https://aws.amazon.com


2. Click Create an AWS Account.


3. Enter:

Email address

Password

AWS account name



4. Enter billing information (card details).


5. Complete phone verification.


6. Choose Basic Support (Free).


7. Your AWS account will be created.




---

2. Login to AWS Console

1. Go to https://aws.amazon.com/console/


2. Click Sign in to the Console.


3. Enter:

Email

Password



4. You will enter the AWS Management Console.




---

3. Create IAM User (Best Practice)

Terraform should not use root account.

1. In AWS console search IAM.


2. Open IAM Dashboard.


3. Click Users → Create user.



Enter:

User name: terraform-user

Check:

✔ Provide user access to AWS Management Console

Click Next.


---

4. Attach Permissions

1. Choose Attach policies directly.


2. Select:



AdministratorAccess

3. Click Next → Create User.




---

5. Create Access Keys

Terraform needs Access Key and Secret Key.

1. Open the created user terraform-user.


2. Click Security credentials.


3. Scroll to Access keys.


4. Click Create access key.



Choose:

Command Line Interface (CLI)

Click Next → Create Access Key.

You will get:

Access Key ID
Secret Access Key

Download the .csv file or copy them.

⚠ Keep them safe.


---

6. Install Terraform

Go to **HashiCorp Terraform website:

https://developer.hashicorp.com/terraform/downloads

Steps:

1. Download Terraform for Windows.


2. Extract the zip file.


3. Copy terraform.exe.



Now paste it in:

C:\Windows\System32

This makes Terraform accessible everywhere.


---

7. Verify Terraform Installation

Open Command Prompt.

Type:

terraform -version

Example output:

Terraform v1.8.x

Terraform is installed successfully.


---

8. Install AWS CLI

Download from:

https://aws.amazon.com/cli/

Install the AWS CLI v2.

After installation check:

aws --version


---

9. Configure AWS Credentials

Run this command:

aws configure

Enter:

AWS Access Key ID: *******
AWS Secret Access Key: ********
Default region name: us-east-1
Default output format: json

Now Terraform can connect to AWS.


---

10. Create Terraform Project Folder

Create a new folder.

Example:

terraform-s3-project

Open the folder.


---

11. Create Terraform File

Create a file:

main.tf

Open it in VS Code or Notepad.


---

12. Add Terraform Configuration

Paste this code:

provider "aws" {
  region = "us-east-1"
}

resource "aws_s3_bucket" "mybucket" {
  bucket = "my-terraform-storage-bucket-12345"

  tags = {
    Name        = "TerraformBucket"
    Environment = "Dev"
  }
}

⚠ Bucket name must be globally unique.

Example:

my-terraform-bucket-2026-123


---

13. Initialize Terraform

Open terminal inside the folder.

Run:

terraform init

Terraform downloads AWS provider.

You will see:

Terraform has been successfully initialized


---

14. Check Terraform Plan

Run:

terraform plan

Terraform will show what it will create.

Example:

+ aws_s3_bucket.mybucket

Meaning it will create an S3 bucket.


---

15. Apply Terraform Configuration

Run:

terraform apply

You will see:

Do you want to perform these actions?

Type:

yes

Press Enter.

Terraform creates the S3 bucket.


---

16. Verify in AWS

1. Open AWS Console.


2. Search S3.


3. Click S3.



You will see the bucket:

my-terraform-storage-bucket-12345

Storage created successfully. 🎉


---

17. Upload File (Optional)

Open bucket.

Click:

Upload → Add files → Upload

Now your storage works.


---

18. Destroy Resources (Optional)

If you want to delete bucket using Terraform:

terraform destroy

Type:

yes

Terraform will remove the bucket.


---

Final Architecture

Terraform
     │
     ▼
AWS Provider
     │
     ▼
Amazon S3 Bucket
     │
     ▼
Storage Created


